OR=#10226A><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FFFFFF>Comment</FONT><B></FONT></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#E5E5E6><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uulaian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ulaian</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>I live here.... get out.</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>4/1/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>11:08:32 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Discussion of PvP tactics</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">I've been thinking about this, in the light of the upcoming ranger BotB. I've come up with some points to help maximize your chances when fighting another ranger:<br>
<br>
Resistances: <br>
When fighting another ranger, you have two resistances to worry about, Magic and Fire. As I see it, your utmost concern will be to get Magic as high as possible, with passing 200 as your goal. Simply put, if you can snare/root your opponent, and he can't land them on you, you control the entire fight. Same goes the other way round, of course, so get that magic resist up.<br>
As for Fire, the reason for this is that all ranger DD's of note are fire based. However, do not sacrifice too much to bring up this resist. And why not? Because using nukes in a PvP fight is not very efficient at all. Even a fully unresisted Calefaction will only do 300 damage, due to the PvP damage reduction on spells, so if your opponent is nuking just heal yourself, which will leave you still with a healthy mana supply once he has spent his on nukes.<br>
<br>
Mana: <br>
Get your Wisdom as high as possible, even if it costs you AC and Hps. With 200wis as opposed to 100, you'll have extra mana for as many as 8 Greater Heals, equating to 2400Hps. And as you spend mana, switch out mana items for Hp/AC items. Removing a Wisdom item will not lower your current mana, unless your max. mana falls below your current. But adding a Hp item later gives you the Hps at once, so equipping it after spending the mana is essentially free. <br>
To take an example, having a 7wis ring equipped at the beginning, you spend 80 mana on something, and then equip a 6ac/65hp ring instead. Those Hps are added to your current Hps, while the removal of 7wis does not affect your current mana. So you get 80 mana at a cost of 0 hps, a very good deal. This does not go for pure mana items, which lower current mana when removed, and will not work with Sta items, which do not increase current Hps when equipped.<br>
However, equipping a number of pure mana items once you've spent all your mana will give you an immediate mana supply again. And you can just remove them again after casting, essentially bringing you below 0 mana, but the game wont mind that.<br>
So, to recap, get wis to 200 for the beginning of the fight, switch out wis items for ac/hp/stat items as you spend the mana, and once oom equip pure mana items when you need to cast, and remove them again when done.<br>
<br>
Nukes/DoTs:<br>
As I already mentioned under resistances, nuking or DoTing is a bad way to spend your mana. With the recast time on Calefaction, and the long casting time on Firestrike and Drones of Doom put into the consideration, just don't do it. Save that mana for healing/buffing yourself, and hope your opponent will spend his on nuking. If he does, just laugh at him and heal yourself, spending half the mana he does.<br>
<br>
Dispelling:<br>
Be prepared to dispell your opponent. If you can get a spell such as SLN or Chloroplast, the will have a huge impact on the fight. Getting rid of that 25pt DS would be nice as well. This is a much better way to spend your mana than nuking, as dispelling SLN will hurt his Hps just as much as landing a full damage Calefaction. For less mana. And will also rid him of some badly needed AC and Regeneration.<br>
<br>
Regeneration: <br>
Use it if you got it. You want a Fungi Tunic if you can get your hands on one, and two of the buffs you choose before start should be Chloroplast and SLN. With these in effect, a lvl 60 ranger should have a standing regen rate of 30pts per tick, which can easily sway a close fight.<br>
<br>
Weapons:<br>
You will want to use a good 2 hander until you manage to drop your opponents damage shield. A high level ranger DS is very ugly, and will literally feed about 50% of your damage back to you if you're using epics. You can't afford to take that mugh damage, so go for the 2 hander. You may do less damage, but its worth it to avoid the DS. Once you get it dropped, go back to your best weapon combo. On an assorted note, don't use kick while your opponent's DS is still up.<br>
There are also some weapons which have extremely helpful procs. Do not, however, bother with weapons that have a slow proc, you have no chance of it getting through the magic resist of a well prepared opponent. What I mean is  weapons such as a Lupine Dagger, if your opponent dispells your wolf form/sow, bring that weapon out until you get a proc, and put it away again. It procs quite often in the primary hand, and it will save you the hassle of recasting in the middle of the fight. And you really want to have that extra movement speed, you really do. And if you can get your hands on a weapon that procs Avatar, use that as well (you didn't need me to tell you that, right?).<br>
<br>
Damage Shields:<br>
Use them, everything you've got. They'll prevent your opponent from using his most damaging weapons, and can well win the fight for you if your opponent is not prepared with a 2 hander.<br>
<br>
Spell setup:<br>
After buffs are done, my take on the spell set up is this, in no particular order:<br>
<br>
Healing spell<br>
Self only DS<br>
Damage shield<br>
Call of Earth<br>
Call of Fire<br>
Dispell<br>
Snare<br>
Root<br>
<br>
This places an emphasis on Damage Shields which can then be recast during the fight, includes Healing as your primary use of mana, and Dispell to drop your opponents buffs. Call of Fire is added for the extra damage, and snare/root because there's always a chance of getting lucky and landing them (which means you win with 90% certainty if you do). SLN and Chloroplast are left out due to taking way too long to cast in combat, and no nukes/DoTs for reasons explained earlier.<br>
<br>
Disciplines:<br>
Trueshot will most likely not be a factor in this. Against a smart opponent you'll never have a chance of getting 2x damage from him standing still, and you would have big trouble getting the distance to your opponent needed for archery. Use Weaponshield if you have it (wait until your opponent is dual wielding if possible, you'll prevent more damage that way), otherwise Resistant. <br>
<br>
Fighting:<br>
You'll want to move around constantly, and if you're confident enough with your controls to pull it off, circle strafe your opponent. Every time he misses an attack because you're not in front of him will help you. Also, if you're using a 2 hander and he is dual wielding, you can back away from him between your hits. This will often result in you being out of range of about 50% of his attacks. Basically turn off auto attack after you make an attack, back off until the icon is no longer greyed out, close for another attack, and repeat. Works best with slow, high damage weapons (I have tested this against a warrior using a weighted axe, it works very well)<br>
<br>
